./.title: Introduction
./.body:
Introduction
The project we will be working on for the next few months is a new Jewlery Inventory web application for a friend. Currently, our friend uses an Excel spreadsheet to handle tracking their current inventory, including pictures, wholesale price, and list price. 
This project will require us to build a full web application from front to back. We will start with an admin page for our friend to interact with. They don't expect this page to be pretty, just functional.
Then we will hook this front-end to a back-end to provide more interactivity to the admin page.
After that, we will delve into databases so that the application will permanently store any data it has.
Finally we will be a nice customer facing front-end for people to search and purchase jewelry.

Unit1/FakeStoreFrontProject.html.title: Store Front Mock Up Project
Unit1/FakeStoreFrontProject.html.body:
Store Front Project
Goal
Using just HTML, build a store front mock up. Think about how you have seen other web store fronts set up (Amazon, eBay, WalMart, etc), and why they put certain things in certain places
Requirements

An index.html file that will be the first page the user sees.
At least 5 different products to sell. 
Each product must have its own .html file
Each product needs at least one picture, shown on both index.html and the product's page


Each product must be on index.html with a link that takes the user to that product's page
Each product page must link back to index.html
Must make good use of HTML tags!

Resources

MDN - Getting Started with HTML
MDN - Creating Hyperlinks (Remember - every page is going to need hyperlinks!)
MDN - Images in HTML (Remember - every product is going to need pictures!)
